<subSubSection id="5DDA5F36A59E302A14D51AA0B0A95B95" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="5F0E0FF414D8549F9D3E246A660E7248" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F9BE362AE25E2BFC702FE19B8B2A6B59" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">
Largest Palaearctic species on the average (body length: male 2.26-2.85 mm, female 2.22-3.05 mm), with lightest head (ochreous to reddish brown anteriorly). Male: abdomen with large and long T5 and S8 (Fig. 2); S1+2 strongly bulging (Figs 1, 2); S5 with longest (in lateral view sinuate) medial, apically forked, process (Figs 2, 11); epandrium with a long dorsolateral seta (Fig. 4); cerci relatively shortly but acutely double-projecting (Fig. 5); gonostylus rather simple (Fig. 3), ventrally somewhat emarginate, with small and short internal subdorsal projection (cf. Fig. 5); hypandrial rod long and slender (Fig. 4); phallapodeme long, with large dorsal keel (Fig. 4); postgonite short and robust; distiphallus with short lateral and ventral lobes and robust funnel-shaped apex (Fig. 6). Female: postabdomen slender, with relatively narrow sclerites of 6
<normalizedToken id="FFDE58672EDE36E95DEB061AEF1F45BA" originalValue="th–">th-</normalizedToken>
8th segment (Figs 7, 8); T8 complete and entirely pigmented (Fig. 7); S8 small, subtrapezoidal, with a small anterior structure (Fig. 8); spermathecae pyriform with conical base (Fig. 10); S10 medially divided (Fig. 8); cerci long and slender (Figs 7-9).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3180FA65551A6DDF58F86284CBCFD5F5" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="192806219C3D2B32C1DC272816F271EE" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4286CFC9E1DDB26E169F3757BF3A4043" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicName id="DC0B213985BD52A72D7CC1D6243706ED" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Herniosina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Herniosina bequaerti" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bequaerti">Herniosina bequaerti</taxonomicName>
is closely associated with subterranean habitats, such as caves (
<bibRefCitation id="1E997D73635E8A7DCCF8B1683428A297" author="Czizek, K" journalOrPublisher="Zeitschrift des maehrischen Landesmuseums, Bruenn" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="13 - 58" title="Beitraege zur rezenten Fauna der maehrischen Hoehlen. 1. Teil." volume="15" year="1916">
<normalizedToken id="BDE31D79ADAB1839AFAA59EC53871F8F" originalValue="Czižek">Czizek</normalizedToken>
1916
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F0C7F9F6D3BECAF42F31427D642AD9C2" author="Duda, O" journalOrPublisher="zoologisch-botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="1 - 240" title="Revision der europaeischen Arten der Gattung Limosina Macquart (Dipteren). Abhandlungen der k. k." volume="10" year="1918">Duda 1918</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="E04F64F286C05AF7967A1AE30DA4C95E" author="Duda, O" editor="Lindner, E" journalOrPublisher="E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" title="Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region" year="1938">1938</bibRefCitation>
; Papp &amp; Plachter 1976), cellars (Pax &amp; Maschke 1935; 
<bibRefCitation id="BDA10065161AD5FD97CF57D7C0F029EA" author="Rohacek, J" journalOrPublisher="Casopis Slezskeho Muzea, Opava (A)" pageId="27" pageNumber="96" pagination="49 - 60" title="Limosinahorrida sp. n., a new species from Czechoslovakia related to Limosinabequaerti (Vill.) (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae)." volume="27" year="1978">
<normalizedToken id="F053F5E94258B4D8FF52D3F955C0472C" originalValue="Roháček">Rohacek</normalizedToken>
1978
</bibRefCitation>
) and burrows, runs and nests of small mammals, including those of rabbits (
<taxonomicName id="9E3169B96473BED4184BCFF541BD62E7" class="Mammalia" family="Leporidae" genus="Oryctolagus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oryctolagus cuniculus" order="Lagomorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cuniculus">Oryctolagus cuniculus</taxonomicName>
), rats (
<taxonomicName id="F6719753E14ED2172792475BB9765BFB" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Rattus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rattus norvegicus" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="norvegicus">Rattus norvegicus</taxonomicName>
), hedgehogs (
<taxonomicName id="0ED884BBF0396B814048A9D6D0FF3E2F" class="Mammalia" family="Erinaceidae" genus="Erinaceus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erinaceus europaeus" order="Erinaceomorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="europaeus">Erinaceus europaeus</taxonomicName>
), moles (
<taxonomicName id="678DCBD1D20D9B0B49E748C9E9E1C37C" class="Mammalia" family="Talpidae" genus="Talpa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Talpa europaea" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="europaea">Talpa europaea</taxonomicName>
), shrews (
<taxonomicName id="E541E9879914958EBDA80FBF333CC77A" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Sorex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sorex araneus" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="araneus">Sorex araneus</taxonomicName>
), mice (
<taxonomicName id="091FBAE3BE0F1C9C76CED8B44689F4D7" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mus musculus" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="musculus">Mus musculus</taxonomicName>
) and voles (
<taxonomicName id="7208AEEFCEC4856F30B4ADCB0A565275" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Microtus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microtus agrestis" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="agrestis">Microtus agrestis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="F20C7089310852095D9E1B63360C0329" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Microtus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Microtus" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Microtus</taxonomicName>
sp., 
<taxonomicName id="7431E69D75820AB46F0460111BE36046" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Arvicola" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Arvicola terrestris" order="Rodentia" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="terrestris">Arvicola terrestris</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="0329AC82DF1EBA17EE16C240DF8EBD51" author="Duda, O" journalOrPublisher="zoologisch-botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="1 - 240" title="Revision der europaeischen Arten der Gattung Limosina Macquart (Dipteren). Abhandlungen der k. k." volume="10" year="1918">Duda 1918</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A662CD07F3E96C1C7A6D33EF4CE82DE9" author="Richards, OW" journalOrPublisher="Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="261 - 345" title="The British species of Sphaeroceridae (Borboridae, Diptera)." volume="1930" year="1930">Richards 1930</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B1119566332F2DC70A56D2CA8E8BA7C2" author="Goddard, WH" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Society for British Entomology" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="235 - 258" title="The description of the puparia of fourteen British species of Sphaeroceridae (Borboridae, Diptera)." volume="5" year="1938">Goddard 1938</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="FAA5812A28029355BC9C9D0C22DD3604" author="Rohacek, J" journalOrPublisher="Casopis Slezskeho Muzea, Opava (A)" pageId="27" pageNumber="96" pagination="49 - 60" title="Limosinahorrida sp. n., a new species from Czechoslovakia related to Limosinabequaerti (Vill.) (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae)." volume="27" year="1978">
<normalizedToken id="09264832045BFFB2062848081A4B2F1F" originalValue="Roháček">Rohacek</normalizedToken>
1978
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F7DD6B86AF4EB961658AC70207563821" author="Rohacek, J" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur Entomologie, Berlin" pageId="27" pageNumber="96" pagination="3 - 195" title="A monograph and reclassification of the previous genus Limosina Macquart (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae) of Europe. Part II." volume="33" year="1983">1983</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8D3FB26E5CFBD6066FB6F1C77F155EB5" author="Rotheray, GE" journalOrPublisher="National Museum of Scotland Information Series" pageId="28" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 46" title="E B Basden's collection of Diptera from bird and mammal nests and mammal runs, burrow and droppings." volume="3" year="1991">Rotheray 1991</bibRefCitation>
). Adults can be also caught by means of soil traps (
<bibRefCitation id="B6769331A02797C7CA2FC806D910EAB0" author="Rohacek, J" journalOrPublisher="Casopis Slezskeho Muzea, Opava (A)" pageId="27" pageNumber="96" pagination="145 - 160" title="Sphaeroceridae (Diptera) collected by the soil trap method in submountaine areas of North Moravia (Czechoslovakia)." volume="29" year="1980">
<normalizedToken id="232116E5F5948DA0BB2E24EB23EEA7BE" originalValue="Roháček">Rohacek</normalizedToken>
1980
</bibRefCitation>
); only very scarcely (migrated specimens) they can be collected outside subterranean habitats (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="039C299FB78E4B3A051B89B866E547C3" author="Grundmann, B" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Arbeitsgemeinschaft Ostwestfaelischlippischer Entomologen" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="31 - 48" title="Die Dungfliegen (Sphaeroceridae) des Sauerlandes. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Dipterenfauna Westfalens." volume="7" year="1991">Grundmann 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2D58BAABC7100073FDA64FF1155D5B11" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">
Because of being adapted to cold and the complete darkness in aphotic parts of caves and having the ability to develop under these conditions, 
<bibRefCitation id="40F033979F5E293CBA6411A757821F23" author="Papp, L" journalOrPublisher="Annales Historico-Naturales Musei Nationalis Hungarici" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="195 - 207" title="On cavedwelling Sphaeroceridae from Hungary and Germany (Diptera)." volume="68" year="1976">Papp and Plachter (1976)</bibRefCitation>
<pageBreakToken id="253406A108CA69065913B2885566661E" pageId="8" pageNumber="77" start="start">classified</pageBreakToken>
<taxonomicName id="7953CE33A23A8FA82EBEA4C68F87DB45" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Herniosina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Herniosina bequaerti" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bequaerti">Herniosina bequaerti</taxonomicName>
as a troglophilous species. They found larvae consuming various decaying media, viz. dead animals, rotten vegetation including wood and/or mycelia of fungi and determined the length of its life-history (from egg to imago) within caves as 70-90 days and the life as an adult being 38 days on the average. The sometimes abundant occurrence of the species in cellars (see 
<bibRefCitation id="9A796068785DA79D9399126427F3878F" author="Rohacek, J" journalOrPublisher="Casopis Slezskeho Muzea, Opava (A)" pageId="27" pageNumber="96" pagination="49 - 60" title="Limosinahorrida sp. n., a new species from Czechoslovakia related to Limosinabequaerti (Vill.) (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae)." volume="27" year="1978">
<normalizedToken id="2A81B812244BBD4A4B42802F8DE993E2" originalValue="Roháček">Rohacek</normalizedToken>
1978
</bibRefCitation>
and material examined), caused by convenient conditions and a rich supply of larval food, can be considered a special case of synanthropy (
<bibRefCitation id="C1FC567241C7563728A01F762F449AFB" author="Rohacek, J" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur Entomologie, Berlin" pageId="27" pageNumber="96" pagination="3 - 195" title="A monograph and reclassification of the previous genus Limosina Macquart (Diptera, Sphaeroceridae) of Europe. Part II." volume="33" year="1983">
<normalizedToken id="4A3C7E72FBF40FFFADA51C557AC46202" originalValue="Roháček">Rohacek</normalizedToken>
1983
</bibRefCitation>
). In burrows of mammals the larvae develop in their droppings and other nest debris (
<bibRefCitation id="4C04659EC3A89BD1C5CF53D8FD703C10" author="Rotheray, GE" journalOrPublisher="National Museum of Scotland Information Series" pageId="28" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 46" title="E B Basden's collection of Diptera from bird and mammal nests and mammal runs, burrow and droppings." volume="3" year="1991">Rotheray 1991</bibRefCitation>
) but obviously much more rapidly due to higher temperature. Adults can occur throughout the whole year. Puparia of 
<taxonomicName id="99279756B44ACCCBF2EA56262EBF70CA" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Herniosina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Herniosina bequaerti" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bequaerti">Herniosina bequaerti</taxonomicName>
were described by 
<bibRefCitation id="7FDAFBEA3F19FE71D36002A0E561CAD6" author="Goddard, WH" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Society for British Entomology" pageId="26" pageNumber="95" pagination="235 - 258" title="The description of the puparia of fourteen British species of Sphaeroceridae (Borboridae, Diptera)." volume="5" year="1938">Goddard (1938)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="B474193FD682D390A16B4C0E97CC19B8" author="Skidmore, P" journalOrPublisher="Dipterist's Digest" pageId="28" pageNumber="97" pagination="6 - 22" title="Notes on the taxonomy of the puparia of British Sphaeroceridae." volume="13" year="1993">Skidmore (1993)</bibRefCitation>
based on specimens found in mouse-runs and on subfossil specimens excavated in an archaeological site in Iceland respectively.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DF9F67DC84AE27669D5545F7441F389C" pageId="8" pageNumber="77" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="4E783E122E0EBF031A45E60D7738B5AC" pageId="8" pageNumber="77">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="123F93D2BFD40A03D521A9B5EFDAF7AC" pageId="8" pageNumber="77">Widespread in Europe (Austria, Belgium, Czech Republic, Finland, Germany, Great Britain, Hungary, Iceland, Ireland, Italy, Latvia, Netherlands, Poland, Slovakia, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland) but surprisingly hitherto unrecorded from its SE part (Balkan peninisula).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
